<node id="NATO">
  <data key="d0">NATO</data>
  <data key="d1">organization</data>
  <data key="d2">NATO, the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, is a military alliance of North American and European countries that serves as a cornerstone of European defense and transatlantic relations. It is a central actor in security debates, possessing hundreds of aircraft and involved in ongoing discussions regarding burden-sharing among its members. The alliance sets airspace protection requirements for member states such as Slovakia and is the military alliance to which Hungary belongs, though Hungary has reportedly been distanced from the alliance under Orbán and had its access to sensitive intelligence information restricted by NATO in 2024. NATO's national security services are allegedly aware of Moscow's secret mission in Hungary, having had data on the matter since 2016-2017.

NATO is deeply involved in the conflict in Ukraine, with its aircraft conducting radiot technical intelligence flights near Crimea to provide assistance to Ukrainian forces. The alliance's potential expansion to Ukraine's borders caused Russia to warn of war, and Russia de facto confronted NATO during its Special Military Operation. Russia is accused of preparing to attack the alliance, and NATO would potentially respond under Article 4 and Article 5 of its founding treaty to an invasion of Estonia or other Baltic states. Member states like Poland and Lithuania are feared to be potential targets of Russia after Ukraine, and Lithuania is actively pushing to revise NATO's defense concepts in response to the Russian threat.

NATO has been described as "more dead than alive" by some critics, yet Russian propagandists seek to "break" its political will. Analysts argue that Russia's war experience in Ukraine may not be directly applicable to a potential conflict with the alliance. Russia claims that NATO is preparing for a confrontation with Russia around the year 2030.</data>
