<node id="Ukraine">
  <data key="d0">Ukraine</data>
  <data key="d1">country</data>
  <data key="d2">Ukraine is a country in Eastern Europe most prominently defined in the 21st century by its full-scale war with Russia, a conflict that shapes its geopolitical situation, military dynamics, and foreign relations. Within this war, Ukraine is characterized as a victim of aggression and a nation actively defending itself, reportedly dominating in FPV drone operations. The war has exposed Europe’s defense limitations and is viewed as a potential precedent for future Russian aggression. North Korean soldiers have fought and died alongside Russian forces against Ukraine, conducting artillery strikes, drone reconnaissance, and being deployed by Russia into Ukrainian territory, including attacks on border settlements and Sumy Oblast. Ukraine holds North Korean prisoners of war and has expressed concerns about cooperation between Russia and North Korea. According to Viktor Orbán, Ukraine’s status was changed from a buffer zone to a potential NATO and EU member as a result of the invasion. Ukraine has participated in peace agreement negotiations with Russia and is the intended beneficiary of sanctions decisions. Its border with Russia is the area where North Korean troops are reported to be stationed.

The country has received substantial international support, including 13 MiG-29 jets from Slovakia in 2023, emergency electricity supplies from Slovakia that were later halted, and diesel exports from Hungary and Slovakia. Its oil pipeline infrastructure has been damaged by Russian strikes, and Ukraine’s section of the Druzhba pipeline was damaged, though Ukraine agreed to the European Union's repair proposal. The government has refused to allow an inspection of this pipeline, and the blockage triggered the seizure of Ukrainian funds by Hungary. A Russian strike targeted the Brody Oil Depot, and Ukraine’s operator Ukrenergo held a contract with the Slovak power system. In December 2025, the European Union allocated €90 billion to Ukraine for budget deficit financing covering 2026–2027, alongside a 90 billion euro loan, and the country could potentially benefit from a reparations loan funded by Russian assets. Ukraine is also described as having sufficient financial resources to last longer than initially expected.

Beyond the war, Ukraine faces significant political tensions with neighboring Hungary. Hungarian leaders, including Viktor Orbán, have accused Ukrainian officials of various actions, such as potentially attacking Hungary, undermining the Nord Stream pipeline, cutting off Slovakia and Hungary from energy supplies, and planning to provoke armed unrest in Hungary. Ukraine’s National Security and Defense Council blocked the Hungarian newspaper Magyar Nemzet. The country has been the target of disinformation regarding the Oschadbank cash and gold bullion theft operation, and diplomatic representatives from Oschadbank confirmed the location of detained vehicles in Hungary. Ukraine has been accused of funding the Tisza Party in Hungary, and it is alleged that Ukrainian criminals were involved in crimes that Sandor Pinter was bribed to cover up. Hungary has suspended transit of supplies intended for Ukraine, and Ukraine has demanded explanations from Hungarian authorities after its citizens were allegedly mistreated in Budapest. Viktor Orbán has described Ukraine as non-independent and criticized it for trying to treat Hungary as a puppet, while also portraying Ukraine as an ungrateful and corrupt neighbor. Ukraine is also alleged to be maintaining an oil blockade against Hungary and Slovakia. Hungary has banned Ukrainian citizens from entering the country, and Ukrainian supporters are perceived as opposition to Orbán.

Ukraine is actively seeking European Union membership and considering opening EU accession negotiations. It receives European aid and sanctions support, though Viktor Orbán has blocked aid and sanctions against the country. Péter Magyar demanded the European Union sever ties with Ukraine until President Volodymyr Zelenskyy apologizes. Hungary has opposed Ukraine’s EU membership, with a Hungarian resolution explicitly opposing it, despite Ukraine receiving financial support from Hungary. Ukraine’s victory in the war is presented as crucial to preventing Hungary from becoming a strategic foothold for Russia. The country is also targeted by the Hungarian intelligence network and is the country where Laszlo Koch currently resides. In the 2000s, spoiler candidate technology was introduced in Ukraine by Moscow political technologists, where the method became entrenched.&lt;SEP&gt;Ukraine is a country that is the recipient of Western aid and the subject of the public opinion survey.&lt;SEP&gt;Ukraine is a country involved in peace negotiations with Russia.&lt;SEP&gt;Ukraine is a country mentioned as a recipient of Western weapon supplies, information about which was allegedly leaked.&lt;SEP&gt;Ukraine is a country that is being helped by European countries through the restoration of their defense industry.&lt;SEP&gt;Ukraine is a country whose forces are described as suffering heavy losses and facing an inevitable defense collapse, and which needs to reform its military.</data>
