  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Russia">
  <data key="d0">Russia</data>
  <data key="d1">country</data>
  <data key="d2">Russia is a country in Eurasia and the modern successor state to the Soviet Union, currently led by President Vladimir Putin and represented diplomatically by Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov. It is actively engaged in a full-scale war against Ukraine, which its government officially refers to as a “Special Military Operation,” though it is accused under international law of initiating the war. The conflict involves Russian drone operators reportedly affected by Starlink disconnections and Ukrainian electronic warfare tactics. Russia has carried out strikes, including one on January 27 that allegedly damaged the Druzhba Pipeline and caused a fire at the Brody oil depot, as well as a missile attack on Mukachevo in August 2025. Despite the war, Russia’s crude oil remains a source for diesel fuel consumed by Ukraine, and Russia has not attacked any EU member state. The war has been described by North Korea’s leader as a “sacred war,” and North Korea’s youth are called to support Russia’s efforts. Russia has conducted negotiations in North Korea and has received about 14,000 North Korean soldiers in 2024, deploying and commanding them in combat operations against Ukraine, with North Korean troops launching artillery strikes from Russian territory and fighting alongside Russian forces. Russia engages in propaganda marches with North Korean soldiers and receives military equipment, ammunition shipments, and military personnel from North Korea, paying predominantly through the transfer of advanced military technologies and industrial orders that have led to improved conditions in North Korea. The Russian defense minister has attended a ceremony in North Korea, and Russia has transferred trophy equipment to North Korea. Russia is also the planned destination for drug supplies from North Korean pharmaceutical companies.

Russia is widely perceived as maintaining an aggressive posture toward European NATO members, with specific allegations of planning potential military operations against Baltic states, such as proposals by Russian propagandists to capture the Estonian city of Narva. Consequently, nations like Lithuania perceive Russia as an aggressor and an existential threat. The European Union identifies Russia as a major security threat that seeks to undermine EU institutions, weaken support for Ukraine, and foster distrust among EU and NATO allies. Russia is accused of conducting a hybrid war against the European Union and NATO, including orchestrating election interference and active measures in Moldova and Hungary, running coordinated information campaigns in Moldova and Romania, and supporting hackers conducting cyberattacks. Russian intelligence services have conducted operations to support Viktor Orbán’s election campaign and influence Hungarian politics. Russia is also alleged to have received confidential EU data from Hungarian Foreign Minister Péter Szijjártó, and EU member states fear Hungary might share information with Russia.

In its bilateral relations, Russia maintains strong diplomatic, economic, and energy ties with Hungary, supplying 90% of Hungary’s oil and 95% of its gas, as well as building Hungary’s nuclear power plant. It supplies discounted oil via the Druzhba pipeline, and Russia has agreed to a 12-point plan with Hungary to strengthen economic, trade, energy, and cultural ties. However, oil transit through the Druzhba pipeline, a condition for certain loans, was halted by Ukraine. Russia is alleged to be the foreign state with which Slovak Prime Minister Robert Fico conspired, and reports indicate that Hungarian aircraft allegedly transported cash and valuables from Russia. Russia is the target of the 20th European Union sanctions package and is accused of secretly influencing Hungary and Slovakia to block EU sanctions. Energy sanctions against Russia have been proposed for lifting by Viktor Orbán, and an inquiry by Orbán concerned Russia’s reaction to a potential EU decision on its assets. Russia is also associated by Hungarian politician Péter Magyar with the style of kompromat used against him, though Magyar is open to negotiations with Russia under certain conditions. Despite sanctions, Russia’s oil remains a desired energy source, and there are mentions of Russia potentially being reintegrated into the global economy. Russia also maintains a long-standing alliance with Iran and is involved in the potential delivery of oil to Cuba. In contrast, the source text states that China, unlike Russia, is a real superpower.&lt;SEP&gt;Russia is the country whose state newspaper, Izvestia, employed Markus Frohnmaier's wife as a journalist.&lt;SEP&gt;Russia is a country involved in peace negotiations with Ukraine.&lt;SEP&gt;Russia is the country suspected of receiving secret European Union documents from the AfD.&lt;SEP&gt;Russia is a country that intends to continue military operations in Ukraine to achieve its strategic goals and is preparing for a potential conflict with NATO.&lt;SEP&gt;Russia is a country whose economy and state-owned companies are severely impacted by a full-scale war.&lt;SEP&gt;Russia is a country to which far-right parties in Germany, France, and Slovakia are close.</data>
