<node id="Hungary">
  <data key="d0">Hungary</data>
  <data key="d1">country</data>
  <data key="d2">Hungary is a Central European country and a member of both the European Union and NATO. Its political landscape has been dominated by Prime Minister Viktor Orbán, who has led the country since 2010. Under his leadership, the electoral system has been described as becoming fictitious, with democratic checks and balances dismantled. Hungary employs a mixed electoral system featuring 106 single-member districts and 93 proportional seats, but has faced allegations of gerrymandering following electoral redistricting by the Fidesz government since 2012, as well as local-level vote-buying and widespread corruption. State media is controlled by the government. Parliamentary elections are held regularly, and Orbán heads into elections scheduled for April 12, which are the subject of alleged Russian interference and an operation known as Operation Budapest. Political figures include Péter Magyar, identified by some as a potential future Prime Minister and opposition leader. Multiple opposition parties decided not to participate in elections to avoid vote splitting and strengthen the Tisza Party. Mass opposition rallies have criticized the government’s pro-Moscow policies, with protests calling for regime change. Elections have been accompanied by disinformation about a Ukrainian connection, and a spoiler candidate tactic, characteristic of post-Soviet political technology, was also used. A bill was submitted to parliament, and separatist agitation banners have appeared on its streets.

Internationally, Hungary’s stance on the war in Ukraine is characterized as both “independent and flexible” and subject to criticism. The country plans to block EU sanctions packages and has worked with Russia to block or delay sanctions, securing an exception to continue buying Russian gas and oil. Hungary disputes damage to the Druzhba pipeline from a Russian strike and did not condemn Russia for the attack. The country has agreed to a 12-point plan with Russia to strengthen economic, trade, energy, and cultural ties, receives Russian oil via the Druzhba pipeline and gas via the Adriatic Pipeline, and fights with Slovakia for the restoration of the Druzhba pipeline. Hungary faces an alleged oil blockade by Ukraine and decided to stop exporting diesel fuel to Ukraine, also suspending the transit of supplies important for Ukraine. Its fighter jets protect Slovakia's airspace. Foreign Minister Szijjártó has confirmed regular communication with Russia’s foreign minister and has been accused of leaking EU documents. The government has been allegedly involved in transporting cash and valuables from Russia, and Hungary’s military intelligence operated an agent network in Ukraine. Hungary has offered assistance to Iran and did not support a joint EU statement on events in Venezuela. Consequently, Hungary has been excluded from official EU meetings and discussions on sensitive topics. Hungary is described as strong and independent yet heavily reliant on Russian energy imports and nuclear power. In a related conflict, Hungary’s minister, János Lázár, admitted to seizing Ukrainian funds in response to Ukraine's blocking of the Druzhba oil pipeline, and Ukraine has demanded explanations from Hungarian authorities regarding the alleged mistreatment of Ukrainian detainees. Orbán has declared that Hungary will not be a puppet of Ukraine, and the government uses anti-Ukrainian propaganda to justify economic problems and claims to protect ethnic Hungarians in neighboring countries. Orbán considers Ukraine an enemy, and Hungary has declared a political war against Ukraine, which it claims is being targeted by intimidation from Ukraine.

Domestically, Hungary faces frozen EU funds due to a lack of anti-corruption reforms, which Orbán described as a declaration of war. The country’s legal system has been referenced in connection with organized crime, including fuel smuggling in the 1990s, and it is a country where Semen Mogilevich controlled companies. Oschadbank's cash-in-transit vehicles were unlawfully detained in Hungary, currently located in Budapest, and Hungary deported seven Ukrainian cash collectors. Former US President Donald Trump expressed love for Hungary and praised Orbán, and Donald Trump Jr. addressed Hungarian citizens. The country has been mentioned as a target of potential U.S. economic investment. Allegations have been made that Brussels bureaucrats undermined Hungary’s economy and energy independence. Political agitation within the country also targets foreign leaders and the European Union. Hungary is expected to receive resumed Russian oil supplies via the Druzhba pipeline.</data>
