<node id="Viktor Orban">
  <data key="d0">Viktor Orban</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Viktor Orbán is a Hungarian politician who has served as Prime Minister of Hungary, first winning national elections in 1998 and returning to the premiership in 2010 as the leader of the Fidesz party, holding power cumulatively for over 16 years. His political career began in 1989 as a student activist fighting communism, with early funding from George Soros, before his ideological stance shifted from liberal to national-conservative around 1994. Orbán has built a political system widely described as controlling state media, campaigning on fear, and using supermajority support to redraw electoral districts, and in 2014, he proclaimed the establishment of a non-liberal state in Hungary. He has personally ensured Hungary’s energy security while using it as a political tool and has refused anti-corruption reforms, leading to frozen European Union funds. Domestically, he has suffered a devastating defeat in the Hungarian elections and conceded, creating a political vacuum, and his regime is now being protested against, with demonstrators demanding his resignation. High voter turnout is considered not very good news for his Fidesz party, and his chances of winning upcoming elections are reportedly decreasing. He is the main political opponent of Peter Magyar, who called Orbán a "traitor" after reports that Moscow plans to conduct an information campaign to keep him in power. Orbán receives political support from the White House administration and has been praised by former U.S. President Donald Trump, including for preventing an invasion of Hungary; he was endorsed by CPAC and supported by Donald Trump, JD Vance, Marco Rubio, and Matt Schlapp. Conversely, he is described as a destructive agent working for both Donald Trump and Vladimir Putin, with his continued leadership linked to potential U.S. economic support.

Orbán has been characterized as a key ally of Vladimir Putin within Europe, cooperating with Russian special services and attempting to turn Hungary eastward economically and politically. He reportedly expressed a willingness to become Putin’s ally during a phone conversation, and he received financial support from Russian mafia figure Semyon Mogilevich for his 1998 election campaign, with suggestions that compromising material may have influenced his later friendliness toward Russia. His staff is suspected of having a "Kremlin connection" based on the use of a spoiler candidate tactic, and a Russian interference operation, Operation Budapest, aimed to preserve his power. He has called for lifting EU sanctions on Russian energy, been accused of sabotaging European Union support for Ukraine, blocked EU sanctions and aid to Ukraine, and refused to diversify energy supplies. He wrote a letter to Vladimir Putin inquiring about Russia's reaction to an EU decision on Russian assets, did not condemn Russia for the strike on the Brody Oil Depot, and has stated that the EU’s plan to strip Budapest of its veto power regarding Ukraine’s EU accession is a declaration of war on Hungary. Orbán has declared a political war against Ukraine, uses the topic of the war in Ukraine in his election campaign, and has used anti-Ukrainian propaganda to justify domestic economic issues and position himself as a "party of peace." He accused Brussels and Kyiv of election interference, defended Hungarian sovereignty, and made statements accusing Ukraine of an oil blockade, blackmail, and threats, while also stating that Hungary will not be a puppet of Ukraine. He made statements about the risks of Ukraine's EU membership and the state of war with Russia, and has allegedly received a death threat from Ukraine. He influences Robert Fico’s actions and shares a pro-Russian stance, and has stated he would block the loan to Ukraine as well as the joint EU statement.&lt;SEP&gt;Viktor Orban is a politician from Hungary who, along with Robert Fico, is expected to unblock €90 billion for Ukraine.&lt;SEP&gt;Viktor Orban is the Hungarian Prime Minister who stated he does not consider Putin an aggressor and blamed the West for starting the war.&lt;SEP&gt;Viktor Orban is the Prime Minister of Hungary whose popularity is declining due to the economic situation, and who is facing a difficult election campaign.&lt;SEP&gt;Viktor Orban is the Hungarian prime minister whose election chances were the target of Russian covert operations, including a proposed staged assassination and media campaign support.&lt;SEP&gt;Viktor Orban is the long-time leader of Hungary who is facing a threat to his power, a situation that affects other geopolitical players.</data>
