<node id="Viktor Orbán">
  <data key="d0">Viktor Orbán</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">Viktor Orbán is a Hungarian politician who has served as the Prime Minister of Hungary for an extended period, having first won national elections in 2010 and remaining in power continuously for over 16 years. He is the leader of the Fidesz party and has also been identified as the Hungarian Minister of Foreign Affairs in certain contexts. Orbán is the father of Gáspár Orbán. He has publicly described himself as a simple rural politician from Felcsút and claimed to have no personal real estate. Supporters describe him as a strong and influential leader capable of keeping Hungary sovereign, while critics note his use of state resources and tactics to secure electoral victories, including allegations of electoral manipulation.

Orbán has faced serious allegations of corruption and personal enrichment, with Peter Magyar accusing him of such misconduct and also alleging that Orbán directed illegal migrants to Slovakia and prematurely released convicted smugglers. He has also been alleged to be involved in a large-scale vote-buying scheme, and Dietmar Clodo reportedly sent money to Orbán. These allegations create a conflicting portrait between the leader’s self-image and the accusations against him.

Orbán is known for his anti-Ukrainian and anti-European rhetoric. He has actively used the Ukraine issue in his election campaigns and has publicly confirmed holding secret negotiations with Vladimir Putin during an election campaign. He has expressed readiness to help Putin, maintains a notable friendship with him, and has blocked EU sanctions and credit against Russia, including blocking €90 billion in EU funds allocated to Ukraine. Orbán made statements about Hungary's interests in Ukraine and Ukraine's alleged actions in Hungary. At an election rally in Győr, he was booed by the crowd and responded by accusing them of promoting Ukrainian interests. He has also responded to slogans of “Glory to Ukraine” with “Glory to Hungary.” Despite his long tenure, some reports indicate he risks losing his position in April elections, and his crushing defeat has been described as a catalyst for Robert Fico. Orbán has been the subject of public support from various international politicians before the Hungarian parliamentary elections and is portrayed in some disinformation campaigns as a strong leader keeping Hungary sovereign.</data>
