<edge source="European Union" target="Hungary">
  <data key="d7">11.0</data>
  <data key="d8">The relationship between the European Union (EU) and Hungary is multifaceted, characterized by formal membership, financial interactions, and significant political conflict. Hungary has been a member of the European Union since 2004. However, its government under Prime Minister Viktor Orbán is in frequent conflict with EU institutions.

A major point of contention involves EU funding. In response to Hungary's failure to implement anti-corruption reforms, the European Union froze approximately 18 billion euros in funds allocated to the country. While the EU normally provides funding to Hungary, this remains blocked, and programs exist aiming to unblock these funds. Financially, Hungary became a net contributor to the EU budget for the first time in 2025 since joining the bloc.

The relationship is further strained over foreign policy, specifically regarding sanctions against Russia. Hungary and Slovakia have secured delays in voting and threatened to block the extension of EU sanctions. Their motivation was to demand the removal of specific Russian individuals from the sanctions list. These EU sanctions have caused a decline in bilateral trade between Hungary and Russia, which certain agreements aim to reverse. The tension escalated when a Hungarian minister proposed sending EU documents to Russian Foreign Minister Сергей Лавров via the Hungarian embassy in Moscow.&lt;SEP&gt;Hungary did not support a joint statement issued by the European Union regarding events in Venezuela.&lt;SEP&gt;Hungary’s resolution includes a point opposing Ukraine’s membership in the European Union, claiming it would involve the EU in war.&lt;SEP&gt;EU countries are increasingly excluding Hungary from sensitive discussions due to fears it may transmit information to Russia.</data>
  <data key="d9">blocking,conflict,diplomatic channel,disagreement,document delivery,exclusion,financial sanctions,funding,funding dispute,funding freeze,information leak,membership,membership opposition,negotiation,net contributor,policy,sanctions,trade impact,war involvement</data>
