<edge source="Ukraine" target="Russia">
  <data key="d7">15.0</data>
  <data key="d8">The relationship between Russia and Ukraine is defined by a state of active war, with Russia engaged in a military conflict against Ukraine. The ongoing war began with Russia’s military operation, referred to by Russian authorities as a "Special Military Operation" (SVO), aimed at achieving specific strategic goals. Ukraine is currently in a state of war with Russia, and the conflict has created significant geopolitical tensions and energy-related issues.

A major point of contention involves the Druzhba oil pipeline. Russia conducted a strike on a pumping station near Brody in Lviv Oblast, damaging the Ukrainian section of the pipeline. In response, Ukraine halted the transit of Russian oil through the pipeline. However, Ukraine has also been noted as being responsible for restoring the transit of Russian oil via this route. The European Union has made a decision concerning the use of Russian assets for a reparations loan for Ukraine.

The war has been further internationalized by the involvement of North Korea. North Korean forces are fighting alongside Russia, and Russia is deploying North Korean troops into Ukraine for combat operations. The outcome of the war could influence the likelihood of a potential Russian attack on the Baltic states, as Russia seeks to weaken European support for Ukraine. Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor Orbán has stated that this war is not the war of Hungary or Europe. Peace negotiations between the two sides have also been discussed as part of the broader conflict.</data>
  <data key="d9">conflict,energy dispute,financial,halted oil transit,military deployment,military operation,military strike,oil transit,peace negotiations,reparations,war,weakening support</data>
