<edge source="Ukraine" target="Hungary">
  <data key="d7">15.0</data>
  <data key="d8">The bilateral relationship between Hungary and Ukraine, particularly under Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor Orbán, has been marked by increasing tension and hostility. Multiple incidents have contributed to this strained dynamic, including a reported death threat allegedly made by a Ukrainian influencer against Prime Minister Orbán, which has further inflamed diplomatic sensitivities. Hungarian officials, including Orbán himself, have been accused of producing anti-Ukrainian propaganda and disseminating false claims about Ukraine. In parallel, disinformation narratives have circulated that inaccurately accuse Ukraine of planning to provoke armed unrest and chaos within Hungary. Observers note that Hungary under Orbán is worsening relations with its neighbor, failing to show solidarity with Ukraine, and instead fostering an atmosphere of hostility. Some reports suggest that Hungary is interested in creating chaos in Ukraine for the purpose of installing a pro-Hungarian government that would serve Hungary's interests, a claim that reflects the deep mutual suspicion characterizing the relationship.

A central point of conflict revolves around energy supplies, specifically the Druzhba oil pipeline. Hungary has stated it will suspend the transit of supplies important to Ukraine until the Druzhba pipeline is relaunched, with Orbán personally linking this condition to Hungary's support for certain sanctions. Ukraine is accused by Orbán of maintaining an oil blockade against Hungary, and Hungary has refused alternative oil supplies from Ukraine despite the supply halt. In response, Hungary seized Ukrainian funds as a retaliatory measure for Ukraine’s blocking of the pipeline. Additionally, Hungary perceives threats from Ukraine against its strategic oil refinery and has taken concrete actions such as deciding to stop exporting diesel fuel to Ukraine.

Beyond energy, diplomatic friction is evident in other areas. Ukraine demands explanations from Hungary over the alleged mistreatment of its citizens in Budapest. Orbán has publicly stated that Ukraine is an enemy of Hungary, citing Kyiv’s demands to Brussels. These actions and statements collectively reflect deep mutual suspicion, with Hungary conditioning its support for Ukraine on the restoration of oil transit and Ukraine viewing Hungary’s actions as hostile.</data>
  <data key="d9">accusation,blackmail,condition,conflict,diesel fuel,diplomatic dispute,diplomatic tension,disinformation,energy,energy trade,enmity,export ban,geopolitical interference,hostility,human rights violation,lack of solidarity,oil blockade,propaganda,refusal of supplies,seizure,strained relations,suspension,threat,transit,transit dispute</data>
