<edge source="Ukraine" target="Viktor Orban">
  <data key="d7">10.0</data>
  <data key="d8">The relation between Ukraine and Viktor Orban is characterized by a series of public statements and political actions from the Hungarian Prime Minister, reflecting a deeply adversarial posture. Orban has explicitly stated he would block a European Union loan to Ukraine until the country restores the transit of Russian oil. He has leveled multiple accusations against Ukraine, including claims that it interfered in Hungarian elections and engaged in "blackmail." Orban has further declared that Hungary "will not become a Ukrainian colony" and insisted that his country "will not be a puppet of Ukraine," while also making contradictory remarks about Ukraine's sovereignty, first suggesting it is not an independent state.

These confrontational statements are a recurrent feature of Orban's political rhetoric, particularly during election campaigns. He utilizes anti-Ukrainian narratives to blame Ukraine for Hungary's economic difficulties, thereby justifying his own domestic policies. For instance, his election propaganda has included messaging that refers to "Ukrainian gold bullion" as a misuse of Hungarian taxpayers' money. This pattern of rhetoric culminated in definitive refusals, such as his statement that he says "no" to Ukraine now, reinforcing a policy of obstruction and public antagonism.&lt;SEP&gt;Viktor Orban, along with Robert Fico, is expected to unblock €90 billion for Ukraine.&lt;SEP&gt;Viktor Orban claimed Ukraine's status was changed from a buffer zone to a potential NATO and EU member.</data>
  <data key="d9">accusation,block,condition,criticism,funding unblocking,geopolitics,hostility,opposition,political statement,propaganda,rhetoric,status change</data>
