<edge source="Russia" target="Viktor Orban">
  <data key="d7">12.0</data>
  <data key="d8">Viktor Orbán’s relationship with Russia is characterized by a close political and economic alignment, personal profit, and public claims of external pressure. Orbán has proposed lifting sanctions on Russian energy to resolve economic and energy crises, and has claimed that Brussels and Kyiv want to cut Hungary off from Russian energy sources. He has offered to assist Russia in any way possible, including in resolving the war against Ukraine, and is actively attempting to turn Hungary eastward, linking it with Russia economically and politically. Orbán’s friendliness toward Russia may stem from compromising material allegedly held by Semyon Mogilevich. Additionally, Orbán is reported to profit personally from cheap Russian oil while the Hungarian population pays high prices.&lt;SEP&gt;Viktor Orban did not condemn Russia for the strike that halted fuel transit.&lt;SEP&gt;The author claims Viktor Orban has been bought by Russia.&lt;SEP&gt;Viktor Orban argued that Russia responded with war after the West changed the European security system without Russia's consent.&lt;SEP&gt;Russia supports Viktor Orban's media campaign and considers him a valuable asset for access to EU discussions.</data>
  <data key="d9">accusation,alleged bribery,assistance,eastern pivot,economic cooperation,economics,energy,failure to condemn,friendliness,friendship,ideological alignment,lifting,political alignment,political interpretation,purchase,sanctions,strategic asset,support</data>
