<edge source="Russia" target="North Korea">
  <data key="d7">16.0</data>
  <data key="d8">The relations between North Korea and Russia have intensified significantly, particularly in the context of the war in Ukraine, evolving into a deep strategic alliance characterized by substantial military, economic, and technological cooperation. This partnership is marked by a consistent policy of political solidarity, with North Korean leader Kim Jong Un expressing explicit support for Russia’s invasion of Ukraine and promising aid. This support is demonstrated through public displays, such as parades where North Korean and Russian flags are carried together, and has led to a formalized exchange of services between the two nations.

Military cooperation is the most prominent aspect of this relationship. North Korea has dramatically increased its military cargo shipments to Russia, sending an estimated 33,000 containers of military equipment, including weapons, ammunition, and artillery pieces. This has included the supply of up to 11 million rounds of ammunition. Beyond materiel, North Korea has directly deployed soldiers to fight alongside Russian forces in Ukraine, with reports of over 10,000 personnel dispatched, including an estimated 14,000 soldiers in 2024. Separately, North Korea sent approximately 5,000 military personnel, including engineers and builders, for infrastructure restoration efforts. The total value of this military assistance—comprising weapons, troops, and logistics—from August 2023 to December 2025 is estimated to be worth between $7.67 billion and $14.4 billion.

The economic and technological dimensions of the relationship are equally significant. Contributing to the Russian military machine has boosted North Korea’s economy, with its GDP growing by 3.7% in 2024. In exchange for its support, North Korea seeks to obtain key military technologies from Russia, particularly those related to spy satellites and nuclear weapons. Russia is reported to have paid for 80% to 96% of the military assistance by transferring advanced and sensitive military technologies and precision components. Additionally, Russia transferred several units of captured military equipment to North Korea for exhibition. This mutually beneficial arrangement has led some observers to characterize North Korea as acting as a “factory for Russia,” a role that has reportedly led to improved conditions for the North Korean state.&lt;SEP&gt;North Korea is preparing to support Russia in the war against Ukraine.</data>
  <data key="d9">alignment,alliance,ammunition supply,economic cooperation,economic impact,gift,increase,industry,logistics,military aid,military alliance,military assistance,military cargo supply,military cooperation,military deployment,military supply,military support,military technology,payment,personnel transfer,promise,soldier deployment,strategic alignment,support,symbolic display,technology exchange,technology transfer,transferred,troop dispatch,trophy equipment,weapons trade</data>
