<edge source="Kremlin" target="Viktor Orban">
  <data key="d7">8.0</data>
  <data key="d8">The relationship between the Kremlin and Viktor Orban is characterized by a complex mix of transactional dealings, perceived asymmetric influence, and political alignment. In 2014, Orban signed a deal with the Kremlin to expand the Paks II nuclear plant. Their direct communication includes a phone call made by Orban in October of an unspecified year to speak with Vladimir Putin, during which Orban expressed readiness to become Putin's mouse.

The Kremlin is perceived to view Orban not as a genuine partner, but rather as a technical tool of influence and an expendable asset. Accusations of direct control are prevalent, with claims that Orban received direct orders from the Kremlin and acted as its puppet. Furthermore, some of Orban's political strategists are suspected of having connections to Kremlin structures, with particular suspicion arising from their use of a spoiler candidate tactic that is characteristic of Kremlin political technologists. At one point, Orban was a key Kremlin ally, but after he lost an election, the Kremlin reportedly attempted to minimize the significance of that loss.</data>
  <data key="d9">alignment,ally,asset,command,communication,connection,control,conversation,deal,influence,loss,political tactics,suspected connection</data>
  <data key="d10">chunk-30533205f101cc1df47f96e15592f2b3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8fa6adba441e776b293e92361b9880d1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4bd0a283b39238236a064e8afb069c87&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ce845ea082895ffef253ac499ba46794&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3117b3a03ff471f00f67b26aade3e091&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e9bcca043358a8f1b8a9a2999a79a6f6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-febe32c9e0da364a16a64ecb34a3ae7b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3311af1794addd390d80bf21ccd47d8f</data>
